00:12:45.335 --> 00:12:46.200
HARPER LIEBLICH: Sure.

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:46.960
AUDIENCE: Better repeat
the question.

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:53.830
LES VOGEL: Yeah, we were asked
for each developer to talk

00:12:53.830 --> 00:12:58.630
about what part of their apps
highlights the Google TV

00:12:58.630 --> 00:13:02.130
experience and what is really
exciting about their apps.

00:13:02.130 --> 00:13:02.880
HARPER LIEBLICH: Yeah.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:09.410
I think, like Les said earlier,
because you can only

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:13.200
fit so much information on the
screen at a time, you have to

00:13:13.200 --> 00:13:18.530
really think clearly about what
it is that's the core of

00:13:18.530 --> 00:13:23.130
your app and why people want to
use it, and remove all of

00:13:23.130 --> 00:13:26.020
the extra bells and whistles
so that you've really got a

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:28.310
clean, easy-to-use experience.

00:13:28.310 --> 00:13:33.980
And it's that focus that for
us was sort of refreshing.

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:38.890
It allowed us to strip away all
of the extraneous things

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:41.670
that we've got going on on our
other platforms, and just

00:13:41.670 --> 00:13:44.390
focus on that core
radio-listening experience.

00:13:44.390 --> 00:13:46.870
So that's one of my favorite
things about it.

00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:52.780
And then the other was the
freedom to really play with

00:13:52.780 --> 00:13:58.490
the visual style and to make
it feel open and inviting.

00:13:58.490 --> 00:14:01.170
