Anyone else in the room
have another question?

00:20:25.895 --> 00:20:26.661
AUDIENCE: I do.

00:20:26.661 --> 00:20:27.643
LES VOGEL: Yeah?

00:20:27.643 --> 00:20:31.276
AUDIENCE: MOVL, can you talk
about building from the living

00:20:31.276 --> 00:20:35.980
room, and then also just the
way you're thinking about

00:20:35.980 --> 00:20:40.710
Google TV and bringing it to,
like, a bar or [INAUDIBLE]?

00:20:40.710 --> 00:20:41.460
ALAN QUEEN: Sure.

00:20:41.460 --> 00:20:45.440
So the question is about how
MOVL is transforming our

00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:49.660
living room games into more
public space applications for

00:20:49.660 --> 00:20:50.910
bars and restaurants
and other things.

00:20:50.910 --> 00:20:54.310
So when we started all this,
we always thought that it

00:20:54.310 --> 00:20:57.490
would be great to take that
multi-screen experience from

00:20:57.490 --> 00:20:59.640
the living room to bars
and restaurants.

00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:02.920
Any bar you go to, I mean if you
guys are going up and down

00:21:02.920 --> 00:21:06.330
Sixth Street, just count the
number of TVs that are in all

00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:07.490
those bars.

00:21:07.490 --> 00:21:11.190
So we see those there and how
many people see those every

00:21:11.190 --> 00:21:13.190
single day and every
single night.

00:21:13.190 --> 00:21:15.850
And imagine if all those
have Google TV on it.

00:21:15.850 --> 00:21:17.570
What would you do with it?

00:21:17.570 --> 00:21:21.180
So the way we approached it
is, we want to have apps

00:21:21.180 --> 00:21:23.765
running on the TV, but then have
everyone else pull out

00:21:23.765 --> 00:21:26.360
their mobile device and
be able to play along.

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:28.430
So it's just as easy as
downloading an app.

00:21:28.430 --> 00:21:32.370
And in a bar you might play
trivia, you might play poker.

00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:33.420
So that's what we're doing.

00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:35.900
We actually have a new product
coming out called The

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:38.210
Neighborhood, which is going
to be launching in several

00:21:38.210 --> 00:21:39.780
bars and restaurants
in the Chicago

00:21:39.780 --> 00:21:41.340
area in a couple weeks.

00:21:41.340 --> 00:21:43.560
And we're hoping to launch that
in many more across the

00:21:43.560 --> 00:21:45.170
country over this year.

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:46.600
But it will allow you
to do just that.

00:21:46.600 --> 00:21:49.330
So you'll be able to walk into
the bar and actually compete

00:21:49.330 --> 00:21:50.100
with other people.

00:21:50.100 --> 00:21:53.920
And it's a really social
experience because the TV on

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:58.300
the wall functions as where
everyone discovers it and

00:21:58.300 --> 00:21:58.930
plays along.

00:21:58.930 --> 00:22:01.080
But they're also connected
to each other.

00:22:01.080 --> 00:22:03.960
So private messaging, chatting,
you can imagine all

00:22:03.960 --> 00:22:06.470
the different things that are
gonna happen in a bar setting

00:22:06.470 --> 00:22:07.820
or a cafe setting.

00:22:07.820 --> 00:22:08.730
It's not just for bars.

00:22:08.730 --> 00:22:12.050
It's actually for retail, bars,
cafes, coffee shops,

00:22:12.050 --> 00:22:12.810
that kind of a thing.

00:22:12.810 --> 00:22:17.120
LES VOGEL: And that can work
with anyone's mobile phone.

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:19.760
Do they download your app or
just go to the website?

00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:22.310
ALAN QUEEN: So we're going to
be doing both versions.

00:22:22.310 --> 00:22:25.110
So you can actually just go to
a URL on your phone, and

00:22:25.110 --> 00:22:26.150
you'll be able to play along.

00:22:26.150 --> 00:22:30.260
And so all the connection
stuff happens via HTML5,

00:22:30.260 --> 00:22:31.520
WebSockets, that kind
of a thing.

00:22:31.520 --> 00:22:34.400
So any HTML5-enabled browser
for mobile phones

00:22:34.400 --> 00:22:35.710
will work just fine.

00:22:35.710 --> 00:22:37.730
And then we'll also have a
downloadable version, so you

00:22:37.730 --> 00:22:40.405
can get to it a little
faster as well.

00:22:40.405 --> 00:22:45.370
LES VOGEL: And Summer asks, how
are mobile devices able to

00:22:45.370 --> 00:22:47.300
interact with the Google TV?

00:22:47.300 --> 00:22:49.460
I'm assuming she's asking
about the SDK.

00:22:49.460 --> 00:22:53.330
ALAN QUEEN: Yeah, so we actually
have a platform and

00:22:53.330 --> 00:22:56.920
an SDK, a set of APIs that
anyone can use to create

00:22:56.920 --> 00:22:59.560
multi-screen applications
for Smart TVs. I

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:00.380
know that's a mouthful.

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:03.900
But if you go to
connect.movl.com, all you have

00:23:03.900 --> 00:23:06.460
to do is sign up and you can
download APIs for iOS,

00:23:06.460 --> 00:23:09.330
Android, JavaScript,
and even Flash.

00:23:09.330 --> 00:23:11.480
And everything is designed from
the ground up around the

00:23:11.480 --> 00:23:13.180
Smart TV experience.

00:23:13.180 --> 00:23:15.520
You create an app on the TV.
We call that the host

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:16.450
application.

00:23:16.450 --> 00:23:19.130
And then you create an app for
your mobile device that acts

00:23:19.130 --> 00:23:20.630
as the companion application.

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:22.250
We call that the controller
application.

00:23:22.250 --> 00:23:24.710
So once all the devices are
connected, you can route

00:23:24.710 --> 00:23:27.100
messages between them and it
doesn't have to be over the

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:28.550
same local Wi-Fi network.

00:23:28.550 --> 00:23:30.180
It actually works through
the cloud as well.

00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:33.670
So you can have TV-to-TV play,
so social in the living room,

00:23:33.670 --> 00:23:36.420
and social across the net,
multi-user, multi-user gaming,

00:23:36.420 --> 00:23:38.116
things like that.

00:23:38.116 --> 00:23:39.060
PETE HOLLENHORST: I--

00:23:39.060 --> 00:23:40.480
ALAN QUEEN: What?

00:23:40.480 --> 00:23:43.100
Oh, oh thank you so much.

00:23:43.100 --> 00:23:44.670
We got a fan, we got a fan.

00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:45.380
LES VOGEL: Yeah.

00:23:45.380 --> 00:23:51.750
And so the camera's not
on it, but your app

00:23:51.750 --> 00:23:54.410
over there has a code.

00:23:54.410 --> 00:23:58.670
They just enter that code and
they're immediately synced.

00:23:58.670 --> 00:23:59.920
ALAN QUEEN: Yeah, it's
really simple.

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:04.310
So on the TV, every TV has a
special pairing code to it,

00:24:04.310 --> 00:24:05.860
and you just enter
it one time.

00:24:05.860 --> 00:24:07.300
Enter the code once.

00:24:07.300 --> 00:24:08.390
It's a five-digit code.

00:24:08.390 --> 00:24:10.040
And then you're connected
to that television.

00:24:10.040 --> 00:24:10.690
LES VOGEL: OK.

00:24:10.690 --> 00:24:13.120
ALAN QUEEN: And then that
television is also connected

00:24:13.120 --> 00:24:14.930
to other televisions and
[INAUDIBLE] down the line.

00:24:14.930 --> 00:24:17.190
And then whatever activity is
happening on that TV at that

00:24:17.190 --> 00:24:20.470
moment, you also see the
companion interface show up on

00:24:20.470 --> 00:24:22.500
your mobile device
at the same time.

00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:23.685
LES VOGEL: Very cool.

00:24:23.685 --> 00:24:25.660
ALAN QUEEN: And then we're going
to extend that too, so

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:29.280
that if you walk into a bar,
it'll be location aware.

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:31.380
So we'll be able to connect
you even easier

00:24:31.380 --> 00:24:32.230
than entering a code.

00:24:32.230 --> 00:24:33.440
LES VOGEL: Oh, that's
a great idea.

